<br>
Modern logic concerns the relationships among propositions.  Logic in this sense can tell you whether an argument is valid or not based upon  the contradiction, implication, or conversion of the propositions.  But logic cannot tell you whether those propositions in and of themselves are valid.<br>
<br>
Thus, an appeal to logic can correctly be used to question the interrelation of propositions in a religion,  it cannot properly question the substance of the proposition itself.  Logic is procedural, not substantive.<br>
<br>
Now that was a summation of modern logic.  The philosophical history of logic is much richer, and goes back to the Greek concept of Logos.  Logos as a concept went through several progressions, but the gist is that there is a controlling principle in the universe.  That the universe unfolds according to the design of Logos. (This unfolding of the universe is where all the drama of existence occurs, through a détente, a relaxation of itself, or in some theories, a corruption of itself).  <br>
<br>
This notion of Logos is religious and philosophical, and was adopted through the Neo-Platonists into nascent Christianity.  For example, in the start of the Book of John, it reads that &quot;in the beginning was Logos (translated as &quot;Word&quot; in most English translations) and the Logos was with God, and the Logos was God. <br>
So we can see that logic in the ancient sense was very much a part of early Christianity.<br>
<br>
However, I think that the posts above where employing a much more sloppy definition of logic.  Wherein popular parlance, logic is bastardized into a normative principle, dictating what is right and wrong based upon perceived notions of common sense, lesser empirical observations, and &quot;reason&quot; (although very much not so the Divine Light of Reason as expounded by the Enlightenment). Exhortations that another party is not being &quot;reasonable&quot; or &quot;logical&quot; is not but a slur indicating that the party does not agree with the slanderer's presuppositions.<br>
<br>
Let me posit without further exploration, that appeals to this sort of logic add no more validity to an argument than an appeal to a biblical source of authority.  Logic abused in this sense is relegated to voodoo.  That you like your voodoo, that it comforts you, that you think it trumps your enemies voodoo, in no way makes it logical.<br>
